  "text": "We propose the innovative parameter, AaBMD, to describe BS and to have potential utility in the management of osteoporosis. The correlations of AaBMD with P max and Fig. 2 The dependencies between vertebral ultimate load (F max ) and densitometric parameters. aBMD antero-poterior DXA areal bone mineral density, AaBMD aBMD adjusted by the anterior to posterior vertebrae heights ratio, vBMD volumetric bone mineral density F max are greater than for the commonly used and widely accepted aBMD obtained using DXA scanning. The correlation is greater both before and after age adjustment. This leads us to the conclusion that AaBMD predicts the mechanical properties of the vertebrae more accurately and would probably also work better as the FR predictor. Several authors believe that vBMD measured by CT is the most reliable parameter in assessing BS and FR due to the fact that CT measurement is not affected by body or skeletal size and properties of the surrounding tissues [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . For the same reason, others claim that P max is a more reliable parameter than F max when considering the mechanical properties of BS [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Even though P max contains adjustments for body and skeletal size, many authors still use F max in their studies, or both P max and F max [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . In our research, we analyzed both parameters mentioned above.",
